 inscribed within discourses of western civilization as regressive and inferior peoples. Over time these discourses increasingly promoted notions of overt and rigid racial hierarchies, of which a legacy still remains.Drawing upon cultural and intellectual history this comparative study seeks to rethink the location of the poor and India within the nineteenth-century imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBritishzIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxPublic opinion. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aEmma Roberts.  aJames Forbes.  aPierce Egan.  acentre and periphery.  acolonial subjects.  aimperial progress.  ametropolitan poor.  anineteenth-century imagination.  aracial hierarchies.  awestern civilization.1 aMarriott, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137838zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137838zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137838/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA